
[1]iniquity

   INIQ'UITY, n. [L. iniquitas; in and oequitas, equity.]

   1. Injustice; unrighteousness; a deviation from rectitude; as the
   iniquity of war; the iniquity of the slave trade.

   2. Want of rectitude in principle; as a malicious prosecution
   originating in the iniquity of the author.

   3. A particular deviation from rectitude; a sin or crime; wickedness;
   any act of injustice.

   Your iniquities have separated between you and your God. Is.59.

   4. Original want of holiness or depravity.

   I was shapen in iniquity. Ps.51.
